/*
 * Edexcel A A-Level Economics (9EC0) — Practice Questions
 * 8 granular topics, 40 questions per topic (320 total), mix of 1-6 marks.
 * Uses markScheme with bullet points and (1) per mark point.
 * Questions requiring diagrams have diagram: true.
 */
const ECONOMICS_EDEXCEL_A_PRACTICE = {
  '1.1': {
    name: 'Nature of Economics & Markets',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State what is meant by the "economic problem".', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Resources are scarce/limited relative to unlimited wants, requiring choices to be made.' },
      { q: 'Define "opportunity cost".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The next best alternative foregone (1) when a choice is made between competing uses of scarce resources.' },
      { q: 'Draw a production possibility frontier (PPF) and show the effect of technological progress in one industry only.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly labelled axes with two goods. (1) Concave PPF curve from axis to axis. (1) Asymmetric outward pivot of the PPF on the axis of the industry experiencing technological progress.' },
      { q: 'Explain, with an example, the difference between a movement along and a shift of the demand curve.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A movement along the demand curve (extension/contraction) is caused by a change in the price of the good itself. (1) Example: a rise in petrol price reduces quantity demanded — movement along. (1) A shift of the demand curve is caused by a change in a non-price determinant (income, tastes, advertising, price of substitutes/complements, population). (1) Example: a rise in income shifts demand for new cars to the right — more demanded at every price.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that determine the price elasticity of supply of a good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The availability of spare capacity/stocks. (1) The time period — supply tends to be more elastic in the longer run as firms can adjust production capacity.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the price elasticity of demand if price rises from £10 to £12 and quantity demanded falls from 100 to 80 units.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) % change in Qd = -20/100 = -20%. % change in P = 2/10 = +20%. (1) PED = -20%/+20% = -1 (unitary elastic).' },
      { q: 'Using a supply and demand diagram, show the effect of a government imposing a specific tax on a good with inelastic demand.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn supply and demand diagram with equilibrium. (1) Supply curve shifts left/up by the amount of the tax. (1) New equilibrium shows higher price and lower quantity. (1) Diagram shows that most of the tax burden falls on consumers (larger price increase relative to producer share) due to inelastic demand.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "consumer surplus" and identify it on a diagram.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Consumer surplus is the difference between what consumers are willing to pay and what they actually pay. (1) Correct supply and demand diagram drawn. (1) Consumer surplus correctly shaded/identified as the area above the price line and below the demand curve.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for income elasticity of demand.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) YED = percentage change in quantity demanded / percentage change in income.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the cross elasticity of demand between two complementary goods is negative.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Complementary goods are consumed together (e.g., printers and ink cartridges). (1) If the price of one rises, demand for it falls, reducing demand for the complement. (1) The positive change in price causes a negative change in quantity demanded of the other good, giving a negative XED value.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain the concept of producer surplus.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply and demand diagram with equilibrium price and quantity marked. (1) Producer surplus identified as the area below the price line and above the supply curve. (1) Explanation: it represents the extra revenue producers receive above the minimum they would accept to supply each unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain two reasons why the demand for water is likely to be price inelastic.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Water is a necessity/essential for life with no close substitutes. (1) Therefore consumers cannot easily reduce consumption even when prices rise. (1) Water bills represent a small proportion of most households\' total income. (1) Therefore price changes have a limited impact on real income and quantity demanded.' },
      { q: 'State the three functions of the price mechanism.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Rationing — allocating scarce goods to those willing and able to pay. (1) Signalling — price changes communicate information to buyers and sellers about scarcity or surplus. (1) Incentivising — price changes motivate producers and consumers to change behaviour (e.g., high prices incentivise new supply).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how the equilibrium price and quantity of coffee would change if the price of tea (a substitute) increased.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium in the coffee market shown with S and D curves. (1) Demand for coffee shifts right (as consumers switch from more expensive tea). (1) New equilibrium shows both higher price and higher quantity of coffee.' },
      { q: 'A firm currently charges £20 for a product. PED is estimated at -0.4. Should the firm raise or lower its price to increase total revenue? Explain.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) PED is inelastic (less than 1 in absolute value). (1) With inelastic demand, raising price will increase total revenue because the percentage fall in quantity demanded is less than the percentage rise in price. (1) Therefore the firm should raise its price.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a point inside the PPF represents an inefficient allocation of resources.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A point inside the PPF means the economy is not using all its available resources or is using them inefficiently. (1) More of one or both goods could be produced without sacrificing production of the other, indicating unemployed or misallocated resources.' },
      { q: 'Define "price elasticity of supply".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A measure of the responsiveness of quantity supplied (1) to a change in the price of a good.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, illustrate the effect of a subsidy on the equilibrium price and quantity in a market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Correctly drawn initial supply and demand diagram with equilibrium P1 and Q1. (1) Supply curve shifts right/down by the amount of the subsidy per unit. (1) New equilibrium shows lower price (P2) and higher quantity (Q2). (1) The subsidy per unit and how it is shared between consumers (lower price) and producers (effective higher price received) can be identified.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply of housing in central London is likely to be price inelastic in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Land in central London is extremely scarce and largely fixed in supply. (1) Planning permission and construction take considerable time, so new builds cannot respond quickly to price increases. (1) Existing housing stock is fixed in the short run — supply cannot increase rapidly even if prices rise substantially.' },
      { q: 'State two conditions under which demand is likely to be price elastic.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The good has many close substitutes available to consumers. (1) The good represents a large proportion of the consumer\'s income/budget.' },
      { q: 'Define "effective demand".', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Demand that is backed by the ability and willingness to pay at the prevailing market price.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a maximum price (price ceiling) set below the equilibrium price.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply and demand diagram with equilibrium price and quantity. (1) Maximum price drawn as a horizontal line below the equilibrium. (1) At the ceiling price, quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied. (1) The resulting excess demand/shortage is clearly identified on the diagram.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a normal good and an inferior good using income elasticity of demand.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A normal good has a positive YED — demand increases as income rises. (1) An inferior good has a negative YED — demand falls as income rises because consumers switch to preferred alternatives. (1) Example: bus travel may be inferior (negative YED) as people switch to car travel when income rises.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the cross elasticity of demand when the price of good A rises by 10% and the quantity demanded of good B falls by 5%. State the relationship between the goods.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) XED = -5% / +10% = -0.5. (1) The negative value indicates the goods are complements (consumed together).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply curve for most goods slopes upward from left to right.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) At higher prices, production becomes more profitable, encouraging existing firms to produce more. (1) Higher prices may cover the increasing marginal costs of production as firms expand output (diminishing returns). (1) New firms may be attracted to enter the market if the price rises sufficiently above their costs.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how the imposition of a minimum price (price floor) above equilibrium creates a surplus.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply and demand diagram with equilibrium marked. (1) Minimum price drawn as a horizontal line above the equilibrium price. (1) At the floor price, quantity supplied exceeds quantity demanded, creating an excess supply/surplus clearly labelled.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "ceteris paribus" and why it is important in economic analysis.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Ceteris paribus means "all other things being equal" — holding all other variables constant. (1) It is important because it allows economists to isolate the effect of one variable on another without confounding influences, making analysis manageable.' },
      { q: 'A good has a YED of +2.5. Explain what this tells us about the nature of the good and how demand responds to income changes.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The positive sign indicates it is a normal good — demand rises with income. (1) The value greater than 1 indicates it is a luxury/superior good with income-elastic demand. (1) A 1% rise in income would lead to a 2.5% rise in quantity demanded — demand is highly responsive to income changes.' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a "free good" and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A free good is one that has no opportunity cost because it is not scarce — it exists in unlimited supply relative to demand. (1) Example: air for breathing (in normal conditions) or sunlight.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a simultaneous increase in demand and decrease in supply affects equilibrium price and quantity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial supply and demand diagram with equilibrium P1 and Q1. (1) Demand curve shifts to the right. (1) Supply curve shifts to the left. (1) New equilibrium shows a definite rise in price but an indeterminate effect on quantity (depends on relative magnitude of shifts).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the PED for a branded product like Coca-Cola is likely to be more elastic than for soft drinks as a whole.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Coca-Cola faces many close substitutes (Pepsi, own-brand colas, other soft drinks). (1) Consumers can easily switch to alternatives if Coca-Cola\'s price rises. (1) The broader category "soft drinks" has fewer substitutes as a whole, so price changes have less effect on total demand for the category.' },
      { q: 'Define "market equilibrium".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The price and quantity at which the quantity demanded equals the quantity supplied. (1) At this point there is no tendency for the price to change — the market clears.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "joint supply" and give an example of how a change in one market affects another.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Joint supply occurs when the production of one good automatically leads to the production of another (by-products). (1) Example: beef and leather — cattle are reared for beef, producing hides as a by-product. (1) If demand for beef rises, supply of leather increases, reducing the price of leather.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the welfare loss to consumers when a monopolist restricts output compared to a competitive market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram showing downward-sloping demand curve and marginal cost. (1) Competitive output at P=MC shown with full consumer surplus triangle. (1) Monopoly output at MR=MC with higher price shown. (1) Loss of consumer surplus identified as the area between the competitive and monopoly outcomes — split into transfer to producer and deadweight loss.' },
      { q: 'Explain why agricultural commodity prices tend to be volatile.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Supply is price inelastic in the short run due to time lags in production (growing seasons, livestock rearing). (1) Supply can shift unpredictably due to weather, disease, or natural disasters. (1) Demand for food is price inelastic (necessity). (1) When both supply and demand are inelastic, any shift in supply causes a large change in price — small changes in harvest can produce dramatic price swings.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between an extension of demand and an increase in demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) An extension of demand is a movement along the demand curve caused by a fall in the good\'s own price (quantity demanded rises). (1) An increase in demand is a rightward shift of the entire demand curve caused by a change in a non-price factor (e.g., higher income, favourable tastes).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the PES of manufactured goods tends to increase over time.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In the very short run, supply is fixed as firms cannot immediately change output. (1) In the short run, firms can use spare capacity and overtime to increase output. (1) In the long run, firms can build new factories, install machinery, and hire workers — supply becomes much more elastic as all factors become variable.' },
      { q: 'Calculate consumer surplus if demand is given by P = 100 - 2Q and the equilibrium price is £60 with quantity of 20 units.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Consumer surplus = 0.5 x base x height = 0.5 x 20 x (100-60). (1) = 0.5 x 20 x 40 = £400.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the demand curve for a Giffen good slopes upward.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A Giffen good is a strongly inferior good where the income effect of a price change outweighs the substitution effect. (1) When its price rises, the real income of very poor consumers falls significantly, forcing them to buy more of the cheap staple (income effect dominates). (1) The substitution effect (buy less as it is relatively dearer) is weaker than the income effect, so overall quantity demanded rises with price.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a negative supply shock (e.g., a natural disaster) affects a market with elastic versus inelastic demand.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Two diagrams: one with elastic demand, one with inelastic demand, both showing leftward supply shift. (1) In both, supply shifts left causing higher price and lower quantity. (1) With inelastic demand, the price rise is large but quantity falls little. (1) With elastic demand, the price rise is smaller but quantity falls more — demonstrating how demand elasticity determines the distribution of the impact.' }
    ]
  },
  '1.2': {
    name: 'Market Failure & Government Intervention',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "market failure".', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) A situation where the free market fails to allocate resources efficiently, resulting in a net welfare loss to society.' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a public good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Non-rival — consumption by one person does not diminish availability for others. (1) Non-excludable — it is impossible to prevent non-payers from benefiting.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a negative externality of production leads to market failure.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram with PMC (private marginal cost) and SMC (social marginal cost) curves, with SMC above PMC. (1) Demand curve (MPB=MSB) shown. (1) Free market equilibrium at PMC=D gives output Q1; socially optimal output at SMC=D gives Q*. (1) Welfare loss (deadweight loss) triangle identified between Q* and Q1, bounded by SMC and demand.' },
      { q: 'Explain why education is considered a merit good.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Education generates positive externalities — an educated workforce benefits society through higher productivity, lower crime, and better health. (1) Consumers may undervalue education due to information failure (myopia/short-sightedness about long-term benefits). (1) Therefore, the free market under-provides and under-consumes education relative to the socially optimal level.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage and one disadvantage of using regulation to reduce pollution.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Advantage: Regulation can set clear limits and enforce compliance quickly, providing certainty about maximum pollution levels. (1) Disadvantage: It does not differentiate between firms\' abatement costs, so may not achieve pollution reduction at minimum cost to society (less cost-effective than market-based instruments).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "asymmetric information" and give one example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Asymmetric information exists when one party to a transaction has more or better information than the other. (1) Example: in the used car market, sellers know more about the true quality and history of a car than buyers. (1) This leads to adverse selection where buyers assume lower quality and are unwilling to pay fair prices, potentially driving good cars out of the market.' },
      { q: 'Define "government failure".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A situation where government intervention in a market (1) results in a net welfare loss or a less efficient allocation of resources than the free market would have achieved.' },
      { q: 'Explain how tradeable pollution permits work to reduce carbon emissions.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The government sets an overall cap on total permitted emissions for an industry/economy. (1) Permits are allocated or auctioned to firms, each allowing a specific amount of emissions. (1) Firms that can reduce emissions cheaply below their allowance sell surplus permits to firms with higher reduction costs. (1) Over time the cap is reduced, lowering total emissions while achieving reductions at minimum overall cost.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a subsidy can correct the under-consumption of a merit good.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram showing MPB (private demand) and MSB (social demand, above MPB due to positive externality). (1) Supply curve (MSC=PMC). (1) Free market equilibrium at MPB=S gives under-consumption. (1) Subsidy shifts supply right (or effectively increases consumption), moving output towards the socially optimal level where MSB=MSC.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the free rider problem prevents private provision of street lighting.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Street lighting is non-excludable — people cannot be prevented from benefiting from it whether or not they pay. (1) Rational individuals will not voluntarily pay as they can free ride on others\' contributions. (1) Without a mechanism to charge consumers, firms cannot generate revenue, so private firms will not provide the good, leading to missing markets.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of government failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Imperfect information — governments may not have accurate data about the true size of externalities, leading to inappropriate policy. (1) Political self-interest — politicians may prioritise re-election over optimal policy, favouring short-term popular decisions over long-term efficiency.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a Pigouvian tax set equal to the marginal external cost achieves the socially optimal outcome.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The tax raises private costs to equal social costs, internalising the externality. (1) Firms now face the full social cost of production in their decision-making. (1) They reduce output to the level where SMC=SMB, which is the socially optimal output, eliminating the deadweight welfare loss.' },
      { q: 'Define "moral hazard" and explain how it represents information failure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Moral hazard occurs when a party takes greater risks because they are insured against or protected from the consequences. (1) Example: a fully insured driver may drive less carefully knowing they are covered. (1) It represents information failure because the insurer cannot fully observe or monitor the behaviour of the insured party after the contract is agreed.' },
      { q: 'State two examples of government failure in the UK economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Agricultural subsidies (e.g., former CAP) leading to overproduction, butter mountains, and environmental damage. (1) The congestion charge in London potentially displacing traffic and pollution to surrounding areas rather than reducing it overall.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the concept of "bounded rationality" from behavioural economics challenges the traditional assumption of rational economic agents.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Traditional economics assumes consumers maximise utility through rational decision-making with full information. (1) Bounded rationality (Simon) argues cognitive limitations prevent people from processing all available information. (1) People use heuristics (mental shortcuts) and are subject to biases (e.g., present bias, anchoring, status quo bias). (1) This means consumers make systematic errors, leading to over- or under-consumption of goods, providing additional justification for government intervention beyond traditional externalities.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the deadweight welfare loss from a negative externality of consumption.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply curve (PMC=SMC). (1) MPB (private demand) above MSB (social demand, which is lower due to negative externality in consumption). (1) Free market equilibrium at S=MPB gives overconsumption at Q1; socially optimal at S=MSB gives Q*. (1) Deadweight loss triangle correctly identified between Q* and Q1.' },
      { q: 'State the Coase theorem and identify one condition necessary for it to work.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The Coase theorem states that if property rights are clearly defined and transaction costs are zero, private bargaining between parties can resolve externalities without government intervention. (1) A necessary condition: transaction costs must be negligible/zero (or property rights must be clearly assigned and enforceable).' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage of using nudge theory to address market failure compared to traditional taxation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Nudges (e.g., default options, framing, simplification) influence behaviour without restricting choice or imposing financial penalties. (1) They preserve individual freedom and autonomy, making them more politically acceptable. (1) They avoid the regressive effects and deadweight losses associated with indirect taxes, while still moving behaviour towards socially optimal outcomes.' },
      { q: 'Explain why common pool resources tend to be over-exploited.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Common pool resources (e.g., fish stocks, common grazing land) are rivalrous but non-excludable. (1) Each individual user has an incentive to exploit the resource as much as possible before others do. (1) Without regulation or property rights, this leads to over-exploitation and potential depletion — the tragedy of the commons.' },
      { q: 'Define "cost-benefit analysis" and state one limitation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) CBA is a technique for assessing the total social costs and benefits of a project, including externalities, to determine whether it yields a net social benefit. (1) Limitation: it is very difficult to place accurate monetary values on intangible costs and benefits such as loss of biodiversity, noise, or community disruption — making results subjective.' },
      { q: 'Define "demerit good" and explain why it is over-consumed in a free market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A demerit good is one that is over-consumed relative to the socially optimal level because consumers do not bear or perceive the full social costs. (1) Consumers suffer from information failure — they underestimate the long-term private costs (e.g., health damage from smoking). (1) Additionally, negative externalities (passive smoking, NHS costs) mean social costs exceed private costs, leading to overconsumption.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a positive externality of production leads to under-production in the free market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram with PMC above SMC (social marginal cost is lower due to external benefits in production). (1) Demand curve (MPB=MSB). (1) Free market equilibrium at PMC=D gives output Q1 (too low). (1) Socially optimal output at SMC=D gives Q* (higher) — welfare loss triangle identified between Q1 and Q*.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "adverse selection" in the insurance market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Adverse selection occurs when asymmetric information leads to a disproportionate number of high-risk individuals purchasing insurance. (1) Insurers cannot perfectly distinguish high-risk from low-risk applicants, so charge an average premium. (1) Low-risk individuals find the premium too high and drop out, leaving mainly high-risk buyers, which may cause market failure or collapse of the insurance market.' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which a government could reduce information failure in healthcare markets.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Mandatory labelling of nutritional content and health warnings on products (e.g., cigarette packaging). (1) Public health campaigns and education programmes to inform consumers about risks and benefits of behaviours.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a ban on a good (e.g., drugs) may lead to government failure.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A ban creates an illegal black market where the good is still traded but without quality controls or safety standards. (1) The government loses potential tax revenue that could be raised from a regulated market. (1) Enforcement costs (policing, courts, prisons) are high and may not reduce consumption significantly. (1) Criminal organisations profit, and associated violence and social harm may exceed the original market failure the ban sought to correct.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the optimal level of output where marginal social benefit equals marginal social cost.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram with MSB (downward-sloping) and MSC (upward-sloping) curves. (1) Socially optimal output identified at the intersection where MSB=MSC. (1) Explanation that at any other output level, welfare could be increased by moving towards Q* — to the left there is under-production (MSB>MSC), to the right over-production (MSC>MSB).' },
      { q: 'Explain why indirect taxes on demerit goods may be regressive.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Indirect taxes take a larger proportion of income from low-income households than from high-income households. (1) Low-income groups may spend a higher share of their income on taxed goods like tobacco and alcohol. (1) This makes the tax burden disproportionately heavy on the poorest, potentially worsening income inequality even if the tax corrects the externality.' },
      { q: 'Define "externality".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A cost or benefit that affects a third party (1) who is not directly involved in the production or consumption of a good or service, and is not reflected in market prices.' },
      { q: 'Explain why property rights can be used to solve the problem of externalities. Give one example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Clearly defined property rights allow affected parties to negotiate compensation or payment for externalities. (1) The polluter or the affected party can bargain to reach an efficient outcome (Coase theorem). (1) Example: if residents have the legal right to clean air, a factory must compensate them or reduce emissions, internalising the external cost.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a private good and a public good.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A private good is excludable — non-payers can be prevented from consuming it. (1) A private good is rival — one person\'s consumption reduces availability for others. (1) A public good is non-excludable — impossible to prevent non-payers from benefiting. (1) A public good is non-rival — one person\'s use does not diminish the amount available for others.' },
      { q: 'Explain how "choice architecture" and default options can be used to improve consumer decision-making.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Choice architecture involves structuring the way choices are presented to influence behaviour without restricting options. (1) Default options exploit status quo bias — most people accept the pre-set option (e.g., automatic enrolment in pensions increases saving rates). (1) This corrects information failure and present bias by guiding consumers towards decisions that improve their long-term welfare.' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why the free market may under-provide research and development (R&D).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) R&D generates positive externalities — knowledge spillovers benefit other firms and society but cannot be fully captured by the innovating firm. (1) R&D is risky and costly with uncertain returns; firms may under-invest if they cannot appropriate sufficient returns, especially where intellectual property protection is weak.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a congestion charge can reduce the negative externalities associated with traffic in cities.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The charge internalises the external costs of driving (pollution, delays to others, noise) by making drivers pay for the congestion they cause. (1) This raises the private cost of driving closer to the social cost. (1) Drivers on the margin switch to public transport, cycling, or avoid peak times, reducing traffic volume. (1) Revenue can be hypothecated to fund improved public transport, further reducing reliance on private cars.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how over-consumption of a good with negative externalities in consumption leads to welfare loss.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply curve (PMC=SMC) drawn. (1) MPB above MSB shown (divergence represents external cost of consumption). (1) Free market output at S=MPB exceeds socially optimal output at S=MSB. (1) Deadweight welfare loss triangle identified between optimal and market output levels.' },
      { q: 'Explain why state provision of a good (e.g., the NHS) may lead to government failure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Without the profit motive and competitive pressure, state providers may lack incentives to minimise costs, leading to X-inefficiency. (1) Political priorities rather than consumer preferences may determine resource allocation (e.g., spending influenced by electoral considerations). (1) Excess demand due to zero price at point of use may lead to rationing, queues, and a mismatch between supply and demand.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between a private cost and a social cost.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A private cost is the cost borne by the individual or firm directly involved in a transaction (e.g., production costs). (1) A social cost includes both private costs and external costs borne by third parties not involved in the transaction (social cost = private cost + external cost).' },
      { q: 'Explain why complete information is a necessary condition for allocative efficiency in a market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Allocative efficiency requires resources to be allocated according to consumer preferences (P=MC). (1) If consumers lack full information about quality, risks, or alternatives, they cannot make rational choices that reflect true valuations. (1) Misallocation results — consumers may over- or under-consume relative to what they would choose with perfect knowledge, leading to welfare loss.' },
      { q: 'Explain how hypothecation of tax revenue can improve the effectiveness of environmental taxes.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Hypothecation means ring-fencing tax revenue for a specific purpose related to the tax (e.g., using fuel duty revenue for green transport). (1) This improves public acceptance of the tax, as people see funds being used to address the problem. (1) It can create a double dividend — reducing the externality through the tax while funding solutions that further reduce environmental damage.' },
      { q: 'State two conditions under which government intervention is most likely to improve market outcomes.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) When the government has good-quality information about the size of the externality or market failure to design appropriate policy. (1) When the intervention can be implemented at low administrative cost and without creating significant unintended consequences or distortions.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "regulatory capture" and how it can cause government failure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Regulatory capture occurs when a regulator acts in the interests of the industry it is supposed to regulate, rather than in the public interest. (1) Firms may lobby, offer future employment, or provide biased information to influence regulatory decisions. (1) This leads to government failure as regulation becomes too weak, favouring producers over consumers and failing to correct the original market failure.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, compare the free market outcome with the socially optimal outcome for a good generating positive externalities of consumption.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply curve (PMC=SMC) drawn. (1) MPB (private demand) below MSB (social demand is higher due to external benefits). (1) Free market equilibrium at S=MPB gives under-consumption at Q1. (1) Socially optimal output at S=MSB gives Q* — welfare gain from moving to Q* shown as the area between MSB and MSC from Q1 to Q*.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.1': {
    name: 'Economic Performance & AD',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State the four components of aggregate demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Consumption (C), Investment (I), Government spending (G), (1) and Net exports (X-M).' },
      { q: 'Define "inflation".', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) A sustained increase in the general/average price level in an economy over time.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between demand-pull and cost-push inflation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Demand-pull inflation occurs when aggregate demand grows faster than aggregate supply, pulling up prices. (1) It is typically associated with a positive output gap and economic boom. (1) Cost-push inflation occurs when rising costs of production (e.g., wages, raw materials, energy) shift SRAS to the left, pushing up the price level. (1) It can occur even when the economy is not at full employment, potentially causing stagflation.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a significant fall in consumer confidence on the price level and real GDP.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium shown with AD and SRAS curves. (1) AD shifts to the left (AD1 to AD2) as consumption falls. (1) New equilibrium shows lower real GDP (Y2 < Y1). (1) Price level falls (P2 < P1) or is shown as lower — deflationary pressure.' },
      { q: 'Define "cyclical unemployment".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Unemployment caused by a lack of aggregate demand (1) during the downturn/recessionary phase of the economic cycle.' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why the unemployment claimant count may underestimate true unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) It excludes those seeking work who are not eligible for unemployment benefits (e.g., some part-time workers, those with savings above the threshold). (1) It excludes discouraged workers who have stopped actively claiming because they believe no suitable jobs are available.' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP per capita may not be a reliable indicator of living standards.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) GDP per capita is an average — it does not reflect income distribution or inequality within a country. (1) It excludes non-marketed output such as household production, volunteering, and the informal economy. (1) It does not account for negative externalities of production (pollution, environmental degradation) that reduce quality of life. (1) It ignores factors like leisure time, personal freedom, and subjective wellbeing.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how a depreciation of the exchange rate could improve the UK current account.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) A diagram or explanation of the Marshall-Lerner condition. (1) Depreciation makes exports cheaper in foreign currency — increasing export volumes. (1) Imports become more expensive in domestic currency — reducing import volumes. (1) If the sum of PED for exports and PED for imports exceeds 1 (Marshall-Lerner condition met), the value of net exports improves, moving the current account towards surplus.' },
      { q: 'State the formula for the multiplier.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) Multiplier = 1 / (1 - MPC) or equivalently 1 / MPW, where MPW is the marginal propensity to withdraw.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the AD curve slopes downward from left to right.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The wealth effect: a lower price level increases the real value of wealth, encouraging more consumption. (1) The interest rate effect: a lower price level reduces demand for money, lowering interest rates, which stimulates investment and consumption. (1) The international trade effect: a lower domestic price level makes exports relatively cheaper and imports relatively dearer, improving net trade (X-M).' },
      { q: 'Explain two factors that could cause the UK current account deficit to worsen.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A rise in the value of the pound (appreciation) makes UK exports more expensive abroad, reducing export volumes. (1) It also makes imports cheaper, increasing import volumes — both worsening the trade balance. (1) Strong domestic economic growth could increase demand for imported goods and services. (1) A loss of competitiveness due to higher domestic inflation relative to trading partners makes UK goods less attractive.' },
      { q: 'Define "the output gap".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The difference between actual real GDP and potential GDP (the maximum sustainable output of the economy). (1) A positive gap means actual output exceeds potential (overheating); a negative gap means spare capacity exists.' },
      { q: 'Explain the relationship shown by the short-run Phillips curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The short-run Phillips curve shows an inverse relationship between unemployment and the rate of inflation. (1) As unemployment falls (economy approaches full capacity), wage pressures increase and demand-pull inflation rises. (1) Policymakers face a trade-off: reducing unemployment may come at the cost of higher inflation, and vice versa.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that influence the level of consumption in an economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Consumer confidence/expectations about future income and job security. (1) Interest rates — lower rates reduce the cost of borrowing and the incentive to save, encouraging consumption.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the accelerator effect links changes in national income to investment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The accelerator theory states that the level of net investment depends on the rate of change of national income/output, not just its level. (1) When GDP growth accelerates, firms need to increase capacity by investing in new capital. (1) When GDP growth slows (even if still positive), net investment may fall — amplifying economic fluctuations.' },
      { q: 'Define "structural unemployment".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Unemployment arising from a long-term decline in certain industries or occupations (1) where workers\' skills no longer match those demanded by growing sectors of the economy.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the balance of payments must always balance in accounting terms.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The balance of payments records all international transactions. (1) A current account deficit (spending more abroad than earning) must be matched by a financial/capital account surplus (net capital inflows to finance the deficit). (1) Any remaining statistical discrepancy is captured by the balancing item/errors and omissions.' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of using CPI as a measure of inflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) CPI uses a fixed basket of goods that may not reflect changing consumption patterns and may take time to include new products. (1) It may not accurately capture quality improvements in goods (substitution bias), potentially overstating the true rate of inflation.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a rise in oil prices could cause stagflation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Rising oil prices increase production costs for firms across the economy (energy, transport, raw materials). (1) This shifts SRAS to the left, causing the price level to rise (cost-push inflation). (1) Simultaneously, higher costs reduce output and increase unemployment — the combination of stagnating/falling output with rising inflation is called stagflation.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, illustrate and explain a positive output gap.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Diagram showing AD intersecting SRAS to the right of the LRAS/potential output level. (1) Actual output (Y1) exceeds potential output (Yf), shown clearly. (1) Explanation: the economy is overheating with unsustainable pressure on resources, associated with demand-pull inflation, labour shortages, and upward wage pressure.' },
      { q: 'Define "real GDP".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The total value of goods and services produced in an economy over a period of time, (1) adjusted for inflation (measured at constant prices) to reflect changes in actual output rather than price changes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the ILO measure and the claimant count measure of unemployment.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The ILO/Labour Force Survey counts anyone without a job who has actively sought work in the last 4 weeks and is available to start within 2 weeks. (1) It is based on a survey sample and follows an internationally agreed standard, allowing comparison between countries. (1) The claimant count measures only those claiming unemployment-related benefits (e.g., Jobseeker\'s Allowance or Universal Credit). (1) It is affected by changes in eligibility rules and tends to give a lower figure than the ILO measure because not all job-seekers claim benefits.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a rise in house prices could increase aggregate demand.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Rising house prices increase household wealth (housing equity effect), making homeowners feel more confident and willing to spend. (1) Higher house prices allow homeowners to borrow more against the increased value of their property (equity withdrawal). (1) Positive wealth effects boost consumer spending, the largest component of AD. (1) Higher house prices may also stimulate housing investment (construction of new homes) as developers anticipate profits.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of frictional unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Workers are temporarily between jobs while searching for new employment that matches their skills and preferences. (1) Information gaps in the labour market mean it takes time for workers to discover and apply for suitable vacancies.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a significant rise in government spending on real GDP and the price level when the economy has spare capacity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium below full employment/potential output. (1) AD shifts to the right. (1) Real GDP increases significantly (negative output gap closes). (1) Price level rises only moderately because the economy was on the relatively elastic section of SRAS (spare capacity absorbs demand increase).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "hysteresis" in the context of unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Hysteresis is the idea that a period of high cyclical unemployment can permanently raise the natural rate of unemployment. (1) Long-term unemployed workers lose skills, motivation, and work habits, becoming less employable even when demand recovers. (1) Employers may use length of unemployment as a screening device, creating a vicious cycle where the long-term unemployed are excluded from hiring.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between a recession and a depression.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A recession is typically defined as two consecutive quarters of negative real GDP growth. (1) A depression is a prolonged and severe downturn — much deeper and longer-lasting than a recession, with very large falls in output and employment (e.g., the 1930s Great Depression).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between deflation and disinflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Deflation is a sustained fall in the general price level (negative inflation rate). (1) Disinflation is a reduction in the rate of inflation — prices are still rising but at a slower pace than before.' },
      { q: 'Explain why deflation may be harmful to an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Consumers may delay purchases expecting further price falls, reducing aggregate demand. (1) The real burden of debt increases (real interest rates rise), squeezing debtors and potentially causing defaults. (1) Firms face falling revenues but sticky nominal wages, squeezing profit margins and leading to job cuts. (1) A deflationary spiral can occur: falling demand leads to lower prices, which leads to further delayed spending and further price falls.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show and explain the effect of a significant increase in net migration on the economy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) LRAS shifts to the right (increased labour supply expands productive potential). (1) AD may also shift right (migrants spend and increase demand for goods and services). (1) If LRAS shift dominates: higher real GDP with limited inflationary pressure. (1) The overall effect depends on whether migrants fill skill gaps (boosting productivity) or primarily increase demand — potentially both output and prices rise.' },
      { q: 'Explain the multiplier process following an initial injection of government spending.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) An initial increase in government spending (e.g., £10bn on infrastructure) creates income for workers and firms. (1) Recipients spend a proportion of their extra income (determined by MPC) on goods and services, creating income for others. (1) This process repeats in successive rounds, with each round being smaller due to withdrawals (saving, taxation, imports). (1) The total increase in national income is a multiple of the original injection: final change in GDP = injection x multiplier.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that determine the size of the multiplier in an economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The marginal propensity to consume — a higher MPC means more of each round of income is re-spent, creating a larger multiplier. (1) The rate of taxation — higher tax rates increase withdrawals, reducing the multiplier effect.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why the multiplier effect may be weak in the UK economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The UK has a high marginal propensity to import — much of any increase in spending leaks abroad as consumers buy imported goods and services. (1) This high withdrawal rate reduces the proportion of income re-spent domestically in each round, weakening the multiplier.' },
      { q: 'Define "gross domestic product" (GDP).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The total monetary value of all finished goods and services produced within a country\'s borders (1) over a specific time period (usually a year or quarter).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a current account deficit is not necessarily a problem for an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The deficit may be financing productive investment — importing capital goods to build capacity that will generate future export earnings. (1) It may reflect a fast-growing economy where strong demand pulls in imports (a sign of economic strength, not weakness). (1) The financial account surplus that finances it may represent attractive investment opportunities drawing in FDI. (1) If the country\'s currency is freely floating, the deficit may self-correct over time through exchange rate adjustment.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the actual growth rate and the trend/potential growth rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The actual growth rate measures the year-on-year percentage change in real GDP — it fluctuates with the business cycle. (1) The trend/potential growth rate is the long-run sustainable rate at which the economy can grow without inflationary pressure (determined by supply-side factors). (1) When actual growth exceeds trend growth, a positive output gap opens; when below, a negative output gap develops.' },
      { q: 'State two costs of unemployment to an economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Lost output — the economy operates below its PPF, resulting in a lower GDP than potential. (1) Fiscal costs — the government loses tax revenue and must increase spending on unemployment benefits, worsening the budget deficit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the economic cycle causes fluctuations in unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) During a boom, rising AD increases output and firms hire more workers, reducing cyclical unemployment. (1) During a recession, falling AD reduces output and firms lay off workers or cease hiring, increasing cyclical unemployment. (1) The time lag between output changes and employment adjustments means unemployment may continue rising after a recession ends (labour hoarding effects).' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a fall in world commodity prices on the UK price level and output.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium with AD and SRAS. (1) SRAS shifts to the right (lower input costs reduce production costs for firms). (1) New equilibrium shows higher real output and a lower price level — a beneficial supply shock.' },
      { q: 'Explain how consumer confidence can lead to self-fulfilling economic downturns.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) If consumers expect a recession, they reduce spending and increase precautionary saving. (1) Lower consumption reduces aggregate demand, leading to falling output and rising unemployment. (1) This confirms the original pessimistic expectations, further reducing confidence — creating a negative feedback loop/self-fulfilling prophecy.' },
      { q: 'State the three approaches to measuring GDP and briefly explain one.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The output/production approach — summing the value added at each stage of production across all sectors. (1) The income approach — summing all incomes earned (wages, profits, rents, interest). (1) The expenditure approach — summing all spending on final goods and services (C+I+G+(X-M)). All three should give the same figure in theory.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.2': {
    name: 'AS, National Income & Macro Policy',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State two injections into the circular flow of income.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Investment (I) — spending by firms on capital goods. (1) Government spending (G) — public expenditure on goods, services, and transfers.' },
      { q: 'Define "monetary policy".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The use of interest rates, money supply, and other monetary instruments (1) by the central bank to influence aggregate demand, inflation, and economic activity.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the multiplier if the marginal propensity to consume is 0.75.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) MPW = 1 - MPC = 1 - 0.75 = 0.25. (1) Multiplier = 1/0.25 = 4.' },
      { q: 'Using a Keynesian AS diagram, show how expansionary fiscal policy can increase real output without causing inflation when there is spare capacity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Keynesian AS curve drawn with horizontal, upward-sloping, and vertical sections. (1) Initial equilibrium on the horizontal section (spare capacity). (1) AD shifts right from AD1 to AD2. (1) Real output increases from Y1 to Y2 with no increase in the price level (still on the horizontal section of AS).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "crowding out".', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Crowding out occurs when increased government borrowing to fund spending raises demand for loanable funds. (1) This pushes up interest rates in financial markets. (1) Higher interest rates reduce private sector investment and consumption, partially or fully offsetting the expansionary effect of the government spending.' },
      { q: 'State two supply-side policies that could shift LRAS to the right.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Government investment in education and training — increasing human capital and labour productivity. (1) Deregulation — reducing barriers to entry and increasing competition, encouraging efficiency and innovation.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a cut in interest rates is transmitted through the economy to affect aggregate demand.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Lower rates reduce the cost of borrowing, encouraging consumers to take out credit and spend more (consumption rises). (1) Lower rates reduce mortgage payments for variable-rate borrowers, increasing disposable income and spending. (1) Lower rates reduce the return on saving, discouraging saving and encouraging spending. (1) Lower rates may cause the exchange rate to depreciate (reduced hot money inflows), making exports cheaper and imports dearer, improving net trade.' },
      { q: 'Define "quantitative easing".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) An unconventional monetary policy where the central bank creates new money electronically (1) to purchase financial assets (usually government bonds) from banks and other institutions to increase the money supply and lower long-term interest rates.' },
      { q: 'Explain why supply-side policies may take a long time to have an effect on the economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Education and training programmes take years before students enter the workforce with improved skills. (1) Infrastructure projects (roads, railways, broadband) have long planning and construction phases. (1) Behavioural responses to tax cuts or deregulation are gradual and uncertain — firms need time to adjust investment plans.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how the classical/monetarist view differs from the Keynesian view on the effectiveness of expansionary fiscal policy.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Classical diagram: vertical LRAS with AD shift right causing only price level increase (no real output gain in long run). (1) This is because in the classical view, the economy self-corrects to full employment. (1) Any short-run output gain is eroded by inflation as wages adjust. (1) Keynesian diagram: with spare capacity, the AS curve is horizontal/flat, so AD shift increases real output without inflation. (1) Keynesians argue the economy can remain below full employment for extended periods. (1) The effectiveness depends on the current state of the economy — fiscal policy is more effective with a large negative output gap and less effective near full capacity.' },
      { q: 'State the Bank of England\'s inflation target and one tool it uses to achieve this.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The target is 2% CPI inflation (symmetric target). (1) The main tool is adjusting the base/bank rate (interest rate) through the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC).' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "Laffer curve".', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The Laffer curve shows the theoretical relationship between tax rates and total tax revenue collected. (1) At very low tax rates, revenue is low; revenue increases as rates rise. (1) Beyond an optimal point, further rate increases reduce revenue because disincentive effects (reduced work effort, tax avoidance/evasion, businesses relocating) outweigh the higher rate.' },
      { q: 'Explain why automatic stabilisers help reduce the severity of economic cycles.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In a recession: progressive tax take falls as incomes decline, and benefit payments rise — both cushion the fall in disposable income and consumption, limiting the contractionary multiplier. (1) In a boom: higher incomes push people into higher tax bands, and fewer claim benefits — both dampen excessive demand growth without deliberate policy action. (1) They operate automatically and immediately without the recognition and implementation lags of discretionary policy.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how an improvement in labour productivity shifts the LRAS curve.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Vertical LRAS curve drawn at initial full employment output (Yf). (1) LRAS shifts to the right to a new higher potential output level (Yf2). (1) Explanation: higher productivity means more output can be produced from the same resources, increasing the economy\'s productive potential.' },
      { q: 'Explain one potential conflict between achieving low unemployment and maintaining low inflation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) As unemployment falls towards and below the natural rate, the labour market tightens. (1) Workers gain bargaining power and firms compete for scarce workers, pushing wages up. (1) Rising wage costs are passed on as higher prices (cost-push inflation) — creating the Phillips curve trade-off between unemployment and inflation.' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of fiscal policy as a macroeconomic tool.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Time lags — recognition, decision-making, and implementation mean fiscal changes may take effect after conditions have changed. (1) Political constraints — decisions may be driven by electoral considerations rather than optimal economic timing.' },
      { q: 'Explain how privatisation is intended to improve supply-side efficiency.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Private ownership introduces the profit motive, incentivising cost reduction and efficiency improvements. (1) Firms face competitive pressure in the market, forcing innovation and better customer service. (1) Shareholder accountability and the threat of takeover discipline management to minimise X-inefficiency.' },
      { q: 'Explain the paradox of thrift and its macroeconomic implications.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) If all households simultaneously increase their saving rate, consumption falls. (1) This reduces aggregate demand through the multiplier effect, lowering national income. (1) Lower income may actually reduce total savings in the economy (even though individual saving rates rose). (1) Implication: what is rational for an individual (saving more) may be harmful for the economy as a whole if done collectively — a fallacy of composition.' },
      { q: 'Define "expansionary fiscal policy".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A deliberate increase in government spending and/or reduction in taxation (1) designed to increase aggregate demand and stimulate economic activity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage of rules-based monetary policy (e.g., inflation targeting) over discretionary policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Rules-based policy provides transparency and predictability, anchoring inflation expectations. (1) This reduces the inflationary bias that might arise from political pressure on policymakers to stimulate the economy before elections. (1) Credible commitment to a target means the central bank needs to do less in practice, as expectations self-fulfil (lower inflation expectations feed into lower wage demands).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a budget deficit and the national debt.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A budget deficit is a flow concept — it occurs in a single year when government spending exceeds tax revenue. (1) The national debt is a stock concept — the total accumulated borrowing (sum of all past deficits minus surpluses). (1) A deficit adds to the national debt each year; the government could run a deficit while the debt-to-GDP ratio still falls if GDP grows faster than the debt.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a contractionary monetary policy (interest rate rise) on AD and the macroeconomy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium with AD and SRAS shown. (1) AD shifts to the left as higher interest rates reduce consumption and investment. (1) Real GDP falls (or growth slows). (1) Price level falls or rises more slowly (downward pressure on inflation).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a government may adopt austerity measures during a period of high national debt.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) To reduce the budget deficit and slow the growth of national debt, restoring fiscal sustainability. (1) To maintain confidence of financial markets and avoid rising bond yields (higher borrowing costs). (1) To reduce the burden of debt interest payments, which divert resources from public services. (1) However, critics argue austerity in a recession reduces AD further, potentially worsening the debt-to-GDP ratio through lower tax revenue.' },
      { q: 'State two supply-side effects of reducing income tax rates.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Increased incentive to work (higher post-tax reward) — may increase labour supply and reduce voluntary unemployment. (1) Greater incentive for entrepreneurship and risk-taking, potentially stimulating business creation and innovation.' },
      { q: 'Explain why forward guidance is used as a monetary policy tool.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Forward guidance involves the central bank communicating its future policy intentions to influence economic expectations. (1) If firms and households expect rates to remain low, they are more likely to borrow and spend now, boosting current AD. (1) It reduces uncertainty in financial markets, helping businesses make investment decisions and reducing long-term interest rates.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between demand-side and supply-side policies in addressing unemployment.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Demand-side policies (fiscal/monetary stimulus) aim to increase AD to create jobs and reduce cyclical/demand-deficient unemployment. (1) They are most appropriate when unemployment is caused by insufficient demand (recession). (1) Supply-side policies (training, labour market reform, tax incentives) aim to reduce structural, frictional, and voluntary unemployment by improving the functioning of labour markets. (1) They target the natural rate of unemployment and increase the economy\'s productive potential.' },
      { q: 'Define "fiscal policy".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The use of government spending and taxation decisions (1) to influence aggregate demand, the distribution of income, and the pattern of economic activity.' },
      { q: 'Explain how infrastructure investment acts as both a demand-side and supply-side policy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Demand-side: the spending creates jobs and income in the short run, increasing AD through the multiplier. (1) Construction workers and suppliers spend their income, generating further rounds of economic activity. (1) Supply-side: completed infrastructure (roads, railways, broadband) reduces transport costs and improves connectivity, raising productivity. (1) This shifts LRAS to the right, increasing the economy\'s long-run potential output without inflationary pressure.' },
      { q: 'State two potential problems with using quantitative easing to stimulate the economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) QE may increase asset prices (shares, housing), benefiting the wealthy disproportionately and worsening inequality. (1) Banks may not lend the extra liquidity to businesses and consumers if confidence is low, weakening the transmission mechanism (liquidity trap).' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the natural rate of unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The natural rate is the level of unemployment that exists when the labour market is in equilibrium — consisting of frictional and structural unemployment. (1) It is consistent with stable inflation (no tendency for inflation to accelerate or decelerate). (1) It cannot be reduced by demand-side policies alone; only supply-side improvements (training, flexibility, information) can lower it.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a simultaneous shift in AD and SRAS to the right on the macroeconomy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial equilibrium shown with AD, SRAS, and LRAS. (1) AD shifts right (increased spending/confidence). (1) SRAS also shifts right (e.g., lower input costs, improved productivity). (1) New equilibrium shows higher real GDP with an ambiguous effect on price level — if both shifts are equal, output rises with stable prices; if AD dominates, prices rise; if SRAS dominates, prices fall.' },
      { q: 'Explain why supply-side policies alone may be insufficient to reduce unemployment in a deep recession.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In a deep recession, the main cause of unemployment is deficient aggregate demand, not structural factors. (1) Even if workers are highly skilled and flexible, they cannot find jobs if firms are not hiring due to insufficient demand. (1) Supply-side policies improve productive potential but do not create the demand needed to utilise that potential — demand-side stimulus is needed first to close the output gap.' },
      { q: 'Explain two advantages of an independent central bank for monetary policy credibility.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Independence removes the temptation for politicians to cut rates before elections for short-term popularity (political business cycle). (1) This anchors inflation expectations because markets trust the central bank to prioritise price stability over political goals. (1) Lower inflation expectations feed into moderate wage demands and pricing decisions, making the inflation target easier to achieve. (1) An independent central bank can take unpopular but necessary decisions (e.g., raising rates in a boom) without electoral pressure.' },
      { q: 'State the three withdrawals (leakages) from the circular flow of income.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Saving (S) — income not spent on consumption. (1) Taxation (T) — income taken by the government. (1) Imports (M) — spending that flows out of the domestic economy to foreign producers.' },
      { q: 'Explain the potential trade-off between economic growth and environmental sustainability.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Economic growth often increases production and consumption, generating pollution, resource depletion, and carbon emissions. (1) GDP growth may come at the cost of environmental degradation if it relies on fossil fuels and unsustainable resource extraction. (1) However, growth can fund investment in clean technology and environmental protection. (1) The relationship is debated — some argue sustainable growth is possible through green innovation, while others argue limits to growth are physical and binding.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the Keynesian and classical views on the shape of the aggregate supply curve.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The Keynesian AS curve has three sections: horizontal (spare capacity), upward-sloping (approaching full employment), and vertical (full capacity). (1) This reflects the idea that prices and wages are sticky downwards and the economy can settle below full employment. (1) The classical/monetarist view shows AS as vertical at full employment output in the long run (LRAS). (1) This reflects the belief that markets clear, wages and prices adjust, and the economy returns to full employment regardless of the price level.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a reduction in corporation tax could shift LRAS to the right.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Lower corporation tax increases post-tax profits, providing firms with more retained earnings for investment in new capital equipment. (1) It may attract foreign direct investment from multinational companies seeking tax-efficient locations. (1) Greater investment increases the capital stock, raising labour productivity and expanding the economy\'s productive capacity (LRAS shifts right).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run effect of a persistent increase in AD beyond full employment output.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Initial long-run equilibrium where AD intersects LRAS. (1) AD shifts right beyond full employment. (1) In the short run, output may temporarily exceed potential (positive output gap) with rising prices. (1) In the long run, SRAS shifts left as wages and input costs rise to reflect higher prices, returning output to potential but at a permanently higher price level — only inflation results.' }
    ]
  },
  '3.1': {
    name: 'Business Growth & Objectives',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "marginal cost".', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) The additional cost of producing one more unit of output.' },
      { q: 'State the profit maximisation condition for a firm.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) A firm maximises profit where marginal revenue equals marginal cost (MR = MC), and MC is rising.' },
      { q: 'A firm produces 500 units at a total cost of £25,000. Calculate the average total cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '(1) ATC = TC/Q = £25,000/500 = £50 per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain the law of diminishing marginal returns.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In the short run, with at least one factor fixed, as successive units of a variable factor are added. (1) The marginal product (additional output) of the variable factor will eventually decline. (1) This causes marginal costs to rise and explains the upward-sloping section of the short-run MC curve.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the relationship between marginal cost and average cost curves.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) U-shaped average cost (AC) curve drawn. (1) U-shaped marginal cost (MC) curve drawn, passing through the minimum point of AC. (1) When MC < AC, average cost is falling. (1) When MC > AC, average cost is rising. MC intersects AC at its minimum point.' },
      { q: 'State two types of internal economies of scale and explain one of them.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Technical economies — large firms can invest in specialised, indivisible capital equipment that operates more efficiently at high volumes. (1) Purchasing/bulk-buying economies — large orders give bargaining power to negotiate lower input prices. (1) (Explanation of either) e.g., Technical: a large car manufacturer can use automated production lines that are only cost-effective at high volumes of output.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between horizontal and vertical integration.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Horizontal integration: a merger/takeover between firms at the same stage of the production process in the same industry. (1) Example: two car manufacturers merging. (1) Vertical integration: a merger between firms at different stages of the same production process. (1) Example: a car manufacturer buying a component supplier (backward) or a dealership (forward).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm might pursue revenue maximisation rather than profit maximisation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Managers may be rewarded based on sales revenue rather than profit (principal-agent problem). (1) Maximising revenue (where MR=0) may increase market share and brand dominance. (1) Higher revenue may deter potential entrants by signalling market dominance and aggressive pricing.' },
      { q: 'Define "minimum efficient scale" (MES).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The smallest level of output at which long-run average costs are minimised, (1) meaning the firm has fully exploited all available economies of scale.' },
      { q: 'State two causes of diseconomies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Communication failures — messages become distorted through long chains of command and bureaucracy. (1) Loss of worker motivation and control — employees feel alienated in very large organisations, reducing productivity.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "normal profit" and its role in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Normal profit is the minimum level of profit required to keep a firm in an industry in the long run (an economic cost). (1) It represents the opportunity cost of the entrepreneur\'s time, capital, and risk-taking. (1) If a firm earns below normal profit in the long run, it will exit the industry; if above (supernormal profit), new firms are attracted to enter.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the "principal-agent problem".', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The principals (shareholders/owners) delegate day-to-day control to agents (managers). (1) Agents may have different objectives — e.g., pursuing growth, prestige, or a quiet life rather than maximising shareholder profit. (1) Information asymmetry means principals cannot perfectly observe or monitor agent behaviour, making it difficult to ensure alignment of interests.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run average cost curve and identify the minimum efficient scale.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) LRAC curve drawn as U-shaped or L-shaped. (1) Economies of scale section (falling LRAC) and diseconomies section (rising LRAC) labelled. (1) MES identified at the output level where LRAC reaches its minimum.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why a firm might pursue sales (output) maximisation as an objective.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Sales maximisation (producing where AC=AR, earning normal profit) maximises output and market share. (1) A larger market share gives greater market power, potential to influence price, and may deter entry by competitors.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a natural monopoly exists and why it may be efficient.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A natural monopoly exists in industries with very high fixed/sunk costs and significant economies of scale (e.g., water pipes, railway networks). (1) The minimum efficient scale is so large relative to market demand that only one firm can operate efficiently. (1) Having one firm avoids wasteful duplication of infrastructure. (1) Average costs would be higher with two or more firms as none would achieve full economies of scale — making monopoly the most productively efficient structure.' },
      { q: 'Define "supernormal profit".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Profit earned above normal profit (1) — where total revenue exceeds total cost including the opportunity cost of all factors of production (TR > TC including normal profit as a cost).' },
      { q: 'Explain two reasons why mergers may fail to deliver the expected benefits to shareholders.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Culture clashes between the merging organisations can reduce productivity and cause key staff to leave. (1) Integration costs (IT systems, rebranding, restructuring) are often underestimated by managers. (1) The acquiring firm may overpay due to managerial hubris or competitive bidding pressure. (1) Diseconomies of scale may emerge as the combined firm becomes too large to manage effectively.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between fixed costs and variable costs with one example of each.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Fixed costs do not change with output in the short run — e.g., rent on a factory building. (1) Variable costs change directly with the level of output — e.g., raw materials used in production.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm might pursue a satisficing objective.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Satisficing means achieving a satisfactory (rather than maximum) level of profit. (1) Managers may lack the information needed to truly maximise profit in complex, uncertain environments. (1) It also allows managers to balance multiple stakeholder interests (workers, customers, community) while keeping shareholders sufficiently content to avoid dismissal.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "creative destruction" (Schumpeter) and its relevance to firm growth.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Creative destruction is the process by which innovative new firms and products destroy existing businesses and industries. (1) It implies that monopoly profits can be temporary if firms fail to innovate — new entrants disrupt markets (e.g., streaming displacing DVDs). (1) Firms must pursue growth and innovation to survive, as resting on current market power risks being disrupted by competitors.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the short run and the long run in the theory of the firm.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The short run is the period in which at least one factor of production is fixed (typically capital) — only variable factors can be adjusted. (1) The long run is the period in which all factors of production are variable — firms can change plant size, enter or exit industries. (1) This distinction determines whether firms experience diminishing returns (short run) or economies/diseconomies of scale (long run).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the short-run cost curves (MC, AVC, ATC) and identify the shut-down point.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) U-shaped AVC, ATC, and MC curves drawn correctly with MC passing through the minimum of both. (1) ATC above AVC (the gap being AFC). (1) Shut-down point identified at minimum AVC. (1) Explanation: if price falls below minimum AVC, the firm cannot cover its variable costs and should cease production in the short run.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "organic growth" and state one advantage over growth by merger.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Organic (internal) growth occurs when a firm expands by increasing its own output, sales, and market share through reinvesting profits, hiring, and developing new products. (1) It avoids the integration problems and culture clashes associated with mergers. (1) It tends to be more sustainable and manageable as growth occurs at a pace the organisation can absorb.' },
      { q: 'Calculate total revenue, total cost, and profit for a firm that sells 200 units at £15 each with average total cost of £12.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) TR = 200 x £15 = £3,000. TC = 200 x £12 = £2,400. (1) Profit = TR - TC = £3,000 - £2,400 = £600 (supernormal profit).' },
      { q: 'Explain how sunk costs can act as a barrier to exit from an industry.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Sunk costs are costs that have been incurred and cannot be recovered on exit (e.g., specialist machinery, advertising, R&D). (1) A firm that has spent heavily on sunk costs may continue operating even when making losses, hoping conditions improve. (1) The inability to recoup these costs makes exit economically painful and keeps firms in the market longer than they otherwise would stay.' },
      { q: 'Define "economies of scope".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Cost savings that arise when a firm produces a range of different products together (1) rather than each product being produced separately by specialised firms — average costs fall due to shared resources, distribution, and marketing.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm may choose to pursue profit satisficing in the short run but profit maximisation in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In the short run, managers may satisfice to balance multiple stakeholder demands and maintain industrial harmony. (1) In the long run, competitive pressure from product and capital markets forces firms towards profit maximisation. (1) Shareholders can replace managers through AGMs, and the threat of takeover (if share price is low due to underperformance) disciplines long-run behaviour.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "conglomerate diversification" and state one potential benefit.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Conglomerate diversification involves a firm expanding into industries unrelated to its existing operations (e.g., Virgin Group in airlines, music, trains). (1) It spreads risk — if one industry enters recession, profits from other sectors can compensate. (1) Additional benefit: financial economies (a larger firm can borrow at lower interest rates) or transfer of managerial expertise across divisions.' },
      { q: 'Explain why average fixed cost declines continuously as output increases.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Fixed costs remain constant regardless of output level. (1) As output rises, the same total fixed cost is spread over more units, so the cost per unit (AFC = TFC/Q) falls continuously — this is "spreading the overhead".' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a firm maximises profit at the output where MR = MC.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping MR and AR/demand curves drawn. (1) U-shaped MC curve intersecting MR. (1) Profit-maximising output clearly identified at Q where MC = MR (and MC is rising). (1) Supernormal profit area shown as the rectangle between AR and AC at the profit-maximising output.' },
      { q: 'Explain why technological change may reduce barriers to entry in some industries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Technology can reduce the MES — digital firms can operate at low scale with minimal fixed costs (e.g., cloud computing eliminates need for physical servers). (1) The internet reduces marketing and distribution costs, allowing small firms to reach customers globally. (1) Open-source software and platforms reduce the capital investment needed to enter technology markets, increasing contestability.' },
      { q: 'State two examples of barriers to entry in a market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) High sunk costs/capital requirements — new entrants need large upfront investment that cannot be recovered if they fail. (1) Legal barriers — patents, licences, or regulatory approvals that restrict who can operate in the market.' },
      { q: 'Explain how performance-related pay can help align the interests of managers and shareholders.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Performance-related pay (e.g., share options, profit bonuses) links managerial reward to company profitability or share price. (1) This gives managers a direct financial incentive to maximise profit rather than pursuing personal objectives. (1) Share options align interests particularly well as managers benefit when the share price rises, which is also the shareholders\' objective.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "predatory pricing" and why it is considered anti-competitive.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Predatory pricing involves a dominant firm deliberately setting prices below cost to drive competitors out of the market. (1) The firm accepts short-run losses, funded by reserves or profits from other markets. (1) Once competitors exit, the firm can raise prices and earn supernormal profit as a monopolist — it reduces competition and harms consumers in the long run.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between total revenue and marginal revenue.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Total revenue is the total income from selling all units of output (TR = P x Q). (1) Marginal revenue is the additional revenue gained from selling one more unit of output (MR = change in TR / change in Q).' },
      { q: 'Explain why firms in industries with high fixed costs and low marginal costs (e.g., airlines, software) often engage in aggressive price competition.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Once fixed costs are committed, the marginal cost of serving one more customer is very low. (1) Each additional sale makes a large contribution to covering fixed costs (high contribution margin). (1) Firms have strong incentives to fill capacity — even low prices above marginal cost contribute to fixed cost recovery. (1) This leads to aggressive discounting, price wars, and yield management as firms compete for marginal customers.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a "demerger" and state one reason a firm might demerge.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A demerger is the splitting of an existing firm into two or more separate, independent companies. (1) A firm might demerge because the combined entity suffers diseconomies of scale — management complexity reduces efficiency. (1) Alternatively, financial markets may value the separate parts more highly than the whole (conglomerate discount), so demerging increases shareholder value.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how an L-shaped LRAC curve differs from a U-shaped one and explain what it implies about diseconomies of scale.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) L-shaped LRAC drawn — costs fall as output increases then flatten at a constant level. (1) Contrast with U-shaped LRAC that eventually rises. (1) The L-shape implies that once MES is reached, firms can continue to grow without experiencing significant diseconomies of scale — constant returns to scale beyond MES.' },
      { q: 'Explain why profit maximisation may be difficult to achieve in practice.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Firms face uncertainty — they may not know their precise demand and cost curves, making it impossible to identify where MR=MC exactly. (1) Complex organisations with multiple products and divisions make it impractical to calculate marginal values for each unit. (1) Firms may use rules of thumb (e.g., cost-plus pricing) rather than marginal analysis due to information constraints and bounded rationality.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "backward vertical integration" and give one advantage for the acquiring firm.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Backward vertical integration occurs when a firm merges with or acquires a supplier at an earlier stage of the production process. (1) Example: a supermarket buying a farm or food processing company. (1) Advantage: it secures a reliable supply of inputs at controlled costs, reducing dependency on external suppliers and protecting against supply disruptions or price increases.' }
    ]
  },
  '3.2': {
    name: 'Market Structures & Labour',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State two conditions required for a market to be perfectly competitive.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Many buyers and sellers, none large enough to influence the market price individually. (1) Homogeneous (identical) products with no differentiation between firms.' },
      { q: 'Define "productive efficiency".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Producing output at the lowest possible average cost, (1) achieved at the minimum point of the average cost curve.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show why a perfectly competitive firm earns only normal profit in the long run.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Individual firm diagram with horizontal demand/AR/MR curve (price taker). (1) U-shaped MC and AC curves drawn. (1) Long-run equilibrium at P = minimum AC (tangent). (1) At this point, MR=MC (profit max) and AR=AC (only normal profit), because any supernormal profit attracts entry until price falls to minimum AC.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "interdependence" in an oligopolistic market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Each firm\'s pricing, output, and marketing decisions are influenced by and affect the decisions of rival firms. (1) A firm cannot set strategy in isolation — it must anticipate and react to competitors\' likely responses.' },
      { q: 'State two forms of non-price competition used by firms in oligopoly.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Heavy advertising and brand-building to create product differentiation and customer loyalty. (1) Product innovation and quality improvements to distinguish their offering from rivals.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, illustrate and explain the deadweight welfare loss from monopoly compared to perfect competition.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Monopoly diagram with downward-sloping D=AR, MR below AR, and MC curve. (1) Monopoly produces at MR=MC, charges price Pm from the demand curve at quantity Qm. (1) Competitive output would be higher (Qc) at P=MC. (1) Consumer surplus under competition is the full triangle above Pc below demand. (1) Under monopoly, part of CS is transferred to producer surplus (rectangle) and part is lost entirely. (1) Deadweight welfare loss triangle identified: the area bounded by demand curve, MC curve, between Qm and Qc — representing lost consumer and producer surplus that no one gains.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopolist might choose not to maximise profit.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The firm may practise limit pricing — setting price below the profit-maximising level to deter entry and maintain long-run market dominance. (1) The firm may pursue sales/revenue maximisation due to managerial objectives (principal-agent problem). (1) It may want to avoid attracting regulatory scrutiny or political attention that very high profits might provoke.' },
      { q: 'Define "marginal revenue product of labour" (MRPL).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The additional revenue generated by employing one more worker, (1) calculated as marginal physical product (MPP) multiplied by marginal revenue (MR).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the demand curve for labour is downward sloping.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The demand for labour is derived from MRPL. (1) Due to diminishing marginal returns, each additional worker adds less to total output (MPP falls). (1) Therefore MRPL falls as more workers are employed, meaning firms will only hire additional workers at lower wages — giving a downward-sloping demand curve.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a trade union can increase wages in a competitive labour market and explain the potential consequence.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Labour market diagram with downward-sloping demand (MRPL) and upward-sloping supply of labour. (1) Union negotiates wage above equilibrium (W_union > W_e). (1) At W_union, quantity of labour supplied exceeds quantity demanded. (1) The gap represents unemployment/excess supply of labour — workers who want to work at that wage but cannot find employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "contestable markets" and why contestability matters for consumer welfare.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A contestable market has low barriers to entry and exit, especially low sunk costs. (1) The threat of potential entry (hit and run) disciplines incumbent firms. (1) Even a firm with high market share must keep prices competitive (limit pricing) to avoid attracting new entrants. (1) This can deliver outcomes similar to competition (lower prices, efficiency) even with few actual firms in the market.' },
      { q: 'State the prisoner\'s dilemma outcome in a two-firm oligopoly game and explain why it occurs.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The Nash equilibrium outcome is for both firms to compete/defect (e.g., both cut prices or advertise heavily) even though mutual cooperation would give higher joint profit. (1) Each firm has a dominant strategy to defect regardless of what the rival does (gaining more if rival cooperates, or losing less if rival also defects). (1) This occurs because of uncertainty about the rival\'s intentions and the individual incentive to gain at the other\'s expense.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between transfer earnings and economic rent in the labour market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Transfer earnings are the minimum payment needed to keep a worker in their current job (their next best alternative wage). (1) Economic rent is any payment above transfer earnings — a surplus the worker receives above what is needed to retain them. (1) For workers with highly unique skills and few alternatives (e.g., top footballers), economic rent is very large; for easily replaceable workers, it is small.' },
      { q: 'Define "monopsony" in the labour market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A labour market with a single or dominant buyer of labour (employer), (1) giving it the power to set wages below the competitive level.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a minimum wage could theoretically increase employment in a monopsony labour market.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A monopsony employer restricts employment below the competitive level and pays wages below MRPL. (1) A minimum wage set above the monopsony wage but below the competitive wage effectively makes the labour supply curve horizontal up to a point. (1) This reduces the marginal cost of hiring additional workers (MCL now equals the minimum wage, not the rising supply curve). (1) The firm now finds it profitable to hire more workers up to where the new MCL equals MRPL — increasing employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why firms in monopolistic competition are said to have "excess capacity" in long-run equilibrium.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) In long-run equilibrium, the demand curve is tangent to the AC curve (AR=AC, normal profit). (1) This tangency occurs on the downward-sloping portion of the AC curve, to the left of minimum AC. (1) The firm could reduce average costs by producing more, but cannot sell additional output profitably — this gap between actual output and minimum-AC output is excess capacity.' },
      { q: 'State two factors that affect the elasticity of demand for labour.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ease of substituting capital for labour — if automation is easy, demand for labour is more elastic. (1) The proportion of total costs accounted for by labour — if labour is a large share, demand is more elastic as wage rises significantly affect total costs.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why wage differentials between male and female workers may persist.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Occupational segregation — women are concentrated in lower-paid sectors (care, retail) while men dominate higher-paid sectors (finance, engineering). (1) Career interruptions for childcare reduce years of experience and progression opportunities. (1) Possible employer discrimination (conscious or unconscious bias) in hiring, promotion, and pay decisions.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show and explain how third-degree price discrimination works.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Two sub-market diagrams shown: one with relatively elastic demand and one with relatively inelastic demand. (1) The firm sets MR=MC in each sub-market separately. (1) A higher price is charged in the inelastic market (where consumers are less responsive to price). (1) A lower price is charged in the elastic market — the firm increases total revenue by charging each group according to their willingness to pay.' },
      { q: 'Explain why X-inefficiency is more likely to exist in a monopoly than under perfect competition.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Under perfect competition, firms face intense competitive pressure — any inefficiency raises costs above price, causing losses and exit. (1) A monopolist, protected by barriers to entry, faces no such competitive threat. (1) Without pressure to minimise costs, managers may allow organisational slack, higher costs, and waste — this is X-inefficiency (costs above the minimum achievable level).' },
      { q: 'Define "allocative efficiency".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Resources are allocated to produce the combination of goods and services most valued by consumers. (1) Achieved where price equals marginal cost (P=MC) in every market.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the kinked demand curve model of oligopoly and explain price rigidity.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Demand curve drawn with a kink at the prevailing price — elastic above, inelastic below. (1) MR curve drawn with a discontinuous (vertical) section at the kink output. (1) Explanation: if a firm raises price, rivals do not follow, so demand is elastic and revenue falls. (1) If a firm cuts price, rivals match, so demand is inelastic and revenue still falls — firms have no incentive to change price, explaining rigidity.' },
      { q: 'Explain the conditions necessary for a firm to practise price discrimination.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The firm must have market power (be a price maker, not a price taker). (1) The firm must be able to separate markets and identify groups with different PEDs (e.g., by age, time, location). (1) Resale/arbitrage must be impossible — consumers in the low-price market cannot resell to those in the high-price market.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the concentration ratio is used to measure market structure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The concentration ratio measures the combined market share of the largest firms in an industry (e.g., CR5 = share of top 5 firms). (1) A high concentration ratio (e.g., >60%) suggests an oligopolistic market structure with significant market power. (1) A low ratio suggests a more competitive market with many small firms. However, it does not reveal the distribution of shares among the top firms.' },
      { q: 'Explain why collusion in an oligopoly is more likely to break down when there are many firms.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) With many firms, it is harder to monitor whether all members are adhering to the agreement. (1) Each firm has a greater incentive to "cheat" (cut price/increase output secretly) as the gain from undercutting is shared among fewer affected rivals. (1) Communication and coordination costs rise with the number of firms, making it harder to agree on and enforce a common price or output level.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run equilibrium in monopolistic competition.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Downward-sloping demand curve (differentiated product) tangent to the AC curve. (1) MR curve below demand, MC curve cutting through. (1) Equilibrium at MR=MC with price on the demand curve at that output. (1) AR=AC at the profit-maximising output — only normal profit is earned; no incentive for entry or exit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply of labour to a particular occupation may be inelastic in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Many occupations require lengthy training or qualifications (e.g., doctors, engineers) that cannot be acquired quickly. (1) Professional regulations or licensing requirements restrict rapid entry. (1) Geographical immobility — workers may be unable to relocate quickly to areas where their skills are in demand.' },
      { q: 'State two ways the government can regulate monopoly power.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Price regulation (e.g., RPI-X price caps) — limiting the prices a monopolist can charge to protect consumers. (1) Competition policy and the CMA — investigating and blocking anti-competitive mergers or practices that reduce competition.' },
      { q: 'Explain how technological unemployment differs from structural unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Technological unemployment is specifically caused by automation or new technology replacing human labour (e.g., robots on production lines). (1) Structural unemployment is a broader concept — it includes all cases where workers\' skills mismatch the needs of growing industries, which may be due to geographical, occupational, or technological change. (1) Technological unemployment is a subset of structural unemployment, but structural unemployment can also arise from trade pattern changes or regional industrial decline unrelated to technology.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopoly may be more dynamically efficient than a perfectly competitive market.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Monopoly supernormal profits provide retained earnings to fund R&D and innovation. (1) Perfectly competitive firms earn only normal profit, leaving no surplus for investment in new technology. (1) Patent protection (a barrier to entry that creates monopoly) rewards innovation and incentivises firms to invest in developing new products. (1) However, the counter-argument is that without competitive pressure, monopolists may lack the incentive to innovate (X-inefficiency extends to innovation).' },
      { q: 'Define "derived demand" for labour.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Labour is demanded not for itself but for the output it produces. (1) The demand for workers is derived from the demand for the goods or services they help produce.' },
      { q: 'Explain two factors that could shift the demand curve for labour to the right in a particular industry.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) An increase in demand for the final product — as more goods are demanded, firms need more workers to produce them (derived demand). (1) This shifts the MRPL curve to the right. (1) An increase in labour productivity (e.g., better training or complementary technology) — each worker produces more output, increasing their MRPL. (1) Firms are willing to hire more workers at each wage level.' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of an oligopolistic market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The market is dominated by a few large firms that together hold a high combined market share. (1) There are significant barriers to entry that protect established firms from new competition.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a bilateral monopoly in the labour market operates and how wages are determined.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A bilateral monopoly exists when a single employer (monopsony) faces a single seller of labour (trade union). (1) The monopsony would prefer to set wages low (below competitive level) while the union would prefer wages high (above competitive level). (1) The actual wage is determined by the relative bargaining power of each side. (1) The outcome is indeterminate in theory — it depends on factors like union membership density, the firm\'s profitability, labour market conditions, and the skill of negotiators.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against price discrimination from the consumer\'s perspective.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) For: some consumers (those with low willingness/ability to pay) gain access to goods they otherwise could not afford — e.g., student discounts, off-peak rail fares. (1) This increases consumer welfare and may be more equitable than a single price. (1) Against: consumers in the inelastic market pay more than they would under a single-price policy — their consumer surplus is extracted by the firm. (1) Price discrimination can feel unfair and reduces total consumer surplus transferred to producer surplus.' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) in the UK.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The CMA investigates proposed mergers that could substantially reduce competition and can block them or require remedies. (1) It investigates anti-competitive practices (cartels, abuse of dominance, restrictive agreements) and can impose fines. (1) It conducts market studies and investigations to identify features of markets that harm consumer interests and can impose remedies.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a monopsony employer determines the wage and employment level.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Upward-sloping labour supply curve (ACL — average cost of labour). (1) MCL (marginal cost of labour) curve above and steeper than supply (because hiring one more worker requires raising wages for all). (1) Employment set where MCL = MRPL (demand for labour). (1) Wage is read off the supply curve at that employment level — below both the competitive wage and the MRPL, showing exploitation.' },
      { q: 'Explain why perfect competition is considered allocatively efficient but monopoly is not.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) In perfect competition, firms produce where P=MC in long-run equilibrium. (1) P=MC means the value consumers place on the last unit (reflected in price) equals the cost of producing it — no misallocation. (1) A monopolist produces where MR=MC, but charges P>MC from the demand curve. (1) Since P>MC, consumers value additional units more than they cost to produce — output is too low and resources are misallocated away from this market, causing deadweight welfare loss.' },
      { q: 'Explain why wages in the public sector (e.g., nursing, teaching) may be influenced by factors other than MRPL.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The public sector does not have easily measurable revenue — services like healthcare and education are not sold at market prices, making MRPL difficult to calculate. (1) Wages are influenced by government budgets, political decisions, and comparability with similar roles. (1) Pay may also reflect equity concerns, recruitment needs, and trade union bargaining rather than marginal productivity theory.' }
    ]
  },
  '4.1': {
    name: 'International Economics & Trade',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "comparative advantage".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ability of a country to produce a good at a lower opportunity cost (1) than another country, providing the basis for mutually beneficial trade.' },
      { q: 'State two benefits of free trade for consumers.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Lower prices resulting from increased competition and specialisation according to comparative advantage. (1) Greater variety and choice of goods and services available from worldwide producers.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effects of a tariff on an imported good on domestic price, quantity, and welfare.', marks: 6, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Domestic supply and demand curves with world price (Pw) below equilibrium shown. (1) At Pw: domestic production is Qs1, consumption is Qd1, imports are Qd1-Qs1. (1) Tariff raises domestic price to Pw+t. (1) Domestic production rises to Qs2, consumption falls to Qd2, imports shrink to Qd2-Qs2. (1) Government revenue rectangle identified (tariff x remaining imports). (1) Deadweight loss triangles identified: production inefficiency (domestic firms producing at higher cost) and consumption inefficiency (consumers priced out).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "trade creation" within a customs union.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade creation occurs when joining a customs union allows a country to switch from a higher-cost domestic source (1) to a lower-cost partner-country source that was previously excluded by tariffs — improving allocative efficiency.' },
      { q: 'State two arguments used to justify protectionist policies.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Infant industry argument — new industries need temporary protection until they achieve economies of scale. (1) National security — protecting strategic industries (defence, energy, food) from foreign dependency.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a floating exchange rate is determined.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The exchange rate is determined by the interaction of supply and demand for the currency on foreign exchange markets. (1) Demand for the currency comes from foreign buyers of exports, foreign investors, and speculators. (1) Supply of the currency comes from domestic importers, outward investors, and those selling the currency — equilibrium is where supply equals demand.' },
      { q: 'Explain two factors that could cause the pound sterling to depreciate.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A cut in UK interest rates reduces the return for foreign investors holding sterling assets, causing capital outflows and reduced demand for the pound. (1) Worsening UK economic data or political uncertainty reduces confidence and increases speculation against the pound. (1) A widening current account deficit means more pounds are being sold to buy imports than are being demanded for exports. (1) Expectations of future depreciation become self-fulfilling as speculators sell sterling.' },
      { q: 'Define "globalisation".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The increasing interconnectedness and integration of world economies (1) through growth in international trade, capital flows, migration, and the spread of technology and ideas.' },
      { q: 'Explain the Marshall-Lerner condition and its relevance to the effect of depreciation on the trade balance.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The Marshall-Lerner condition states that a depreciation will improve the trade balance if the sum of PED for exports and PED for imports is greater than 1. (1) Depreciation makes exports cheaper and imports dearer. (1) If demand is sufficiently elastic, export volumes rise and import volumes fall enough to outweigh the adverse price effects. (1) If the condition is not met (demand is inelastic), the trade balance worsens because the volume changes are too small to offset the changed prices.' },
      { q: 'State two features of a single market (e.g., the EU single market).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Free movement of goods and services between member states without tariffs, quotas, or border checks. (1) Free movement of capital and labour — workers can live and work in any member state, and firms can invest freely across borders.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a free trade area and a customs union.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A free trade area (e.g., NAFTA/USMCA) removes tariffs between members but each country sets its own external tariffs on non-members. (1) A customs union (e.g., the EU) removes internal tariffs AND adopts a common external tariff (CET) on imports from non-members. (1) The CET means members cannot negotiate individual trade deals with non-members (trade policy is collective).' },
      { q: 'Explain the J-curve effect following a depreciation of the currency.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Immediately after depreciation, the trade balance worsens because import prices rise in domestic currency but volumes are unchanged in the short run (contracts already agreed). (1) Over time, volumes adjust: export demand rises (cheaper) and import demand falls (dearer). (1) Eventually the trade balance improves — the pattern of initial worsening followed by improvement traces a J-shape over time.' },
      { q: 'Define "terms of trade".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The ratio of a country\'s average export prices to its average import prices, (1) expressed as an index: (Index of export prices / Index of import prices) x 100.' },
      { q: 'Explain one benefit and one cost of foreign direct investment for a developing country.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Benefit: FDI brings capital, creates employment opportunities, and may transfer technology and management skills to the host economy. (1) This can fill the savings/investment gap and accelerate industrialisation. (1) Cost: Profits may be repatriated to the home country rather than reinvested locally, creating a leakage from the domestic economy. (1) MNCs may exploit weak regulations (environmental, labour), extracting resources without sustainable benefits for the host population.' },
      { q: 'Explain why "hot money flows" can cause exchange rate instability.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Hot money is short-term speculative capital that moves rapidly between countries seeking the highest return or safest haven. (1) Large sudden inflows can cause sharp currency appreciation, harming export competitiveness. (1) Sudden outflows (capital flight) cause rapid depreciation, increasing import costs and inflation — this volatility creates uncertainty that deters long-term trade and investment.' },
      { q: 'State two potential disadvantages of a country joining a monetary union.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Loss of independent monetary policy — the country cannot set its own interest rates to address domestic economic conditions. (1) Inability to adjust the exchange rate — cannot depreciate to restore competitiveness during an asymmetric economic shock.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "dumping" in international trade and why it may be harmful.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Dumping is the practice of exporting goods at a price below the cost of production or below the home market price. (1) It may be used to destroy foreign competitors and gain market share (predatory dumping). (1) It harms domestic producers in the importing country who cannot compete with below-cost prices, potentially destroying industries and jobs.' },
      { q: 'Explain why some economists argue that the WTO has failed developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Agricultural subsidies in developed countries (EU, US) make it very difficult for developing country farmers to compete on world markets. (1) WTO negotiating rounds have stalled on issues important to developing countries (e.g., agricultural market access). (1) Intellectual property rules (TRIPS) can restrict access to essential medicines and technologies. (1) Developing countries often lack the legal and technical capacity to bring and win dispute cases against larger economies.' },
      { q: 'Define "trade diversion".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade diversion occurs when the formation of a trading bloc causes imports to switch from a more efficient non-member producer (1) to a less efficient member producer due to the common external tariff making non-member goods relatively more expensive.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a fixed and a floating exchange rate system.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) A fixed exchange rate is set by the government/central bank and maintained through foreign exchange market intervention (buying/selling reserves). (1) It provides certainty for trade but requires large reserves and constrains monetary policy. (1) A floating exchange rate is determined freely by market supply and demand with no government intervention. (1) It adjusts automatically to economic conditions and allows independent monetary policy, but creates exchange rate uncertainty for traders and investors.' },
      { q: 'State the principle of absolute advantage and how it differs from comparative advantage.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Absolute advantage exists when a country can produce a good using fewer resources (more efficiently) than another country. (1) Comparative advantage is based on lower opportunity cost, not absolute efficiency. (1) A country can have a comparative advantage in a good even if another country has the absolute advantage in producing all goods — trade is still mutually beneficial.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of an import quota on the domestic market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Domestic supply and demand with world price shown. (1) Quota restricts imports to a fixed quantity (shown as horizontal distance). (1) Domestic price rises above world price because import supply is limited. (1) Domestic producers gain (higher price, more output) but consumers lose (higher price, less consumption) — welfare effects similar to a tariff but no government revenue (quota rents go to importers or foreign firms).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a managed (dirty) float exchange rate system operates.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The exchange rate is primarily determined by market forces of supply and demand. (1) However, the central bank intervenes occasionally to smooth excessive fluctuations or to prevent destabilising appreciation/depreciation. (1) This aims to combine the benefits of floating (automatic adjustment) with some of the stability of a fixed rate, without committing large reserves permanently.' },
      { q: 'Explain two limitations of the theory of comparative advantage.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) It assumes no transport costs — in reality, transport costs may outweigh the cost advantage of specialisation. (1) It assumes constant costs of production — in practice, increasing specialisation may lead to rising costs (diminishing returns). (1) It ignores dynamic comparative advantage — countries can develop new advantages through industrial policy, investment, and learning. (1) It assumes free trade and perfect factor mobility within countries, which often do not hold in practice.' },
      { q: 'Define "current account" of the balance of payments.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The section of the balance of payments that records trade in goods, trade in services, primary income (investment income), (1) and secondary income (transfers such as overseas aid and remittances).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a strong (appreciated) currency may harm economic growth.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) A strong currency makes exports more expensive in foreign markets, reducing demand for exports and potentially causing job losses in export industries. (1) Imports become cheaper, increasing import penetration and reducing demand for domestically produced goods. (1) Reduced net exports decrease aggregate demand, slowing economic growth and potentially widening the current account deficit.' },
      { q: 'Explain the potential impact of Brexit on UK trade with EU countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Leaving the EU single market and customs union introduced non-tariff barriers (customs checks, regulatory divergence, rules of origin) increasing trade costs. (1) Some firms face new tariffs on goods that do not meet rules of origin requirements. (1) Services trade (important for the UK) lost passporting rights and mutual recognition of qualifications. (1) However, the UK gained the ability to negotiate independent trade deals with non-EU countries, potentially opening new markets.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how an appreciation of the exchange rate affects the market for UK exports.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Supply and demand diagram for UK exports priced in foreign currency. (1) Appreciation means UK exports become more expensive in foreign currency — demand for exports shifts left (or supply shifts up from foreign buyers\' perspective). (1) Quantity of exports demanded falls, reducing UK export revenue — shown as movement to new equilibrium with lower quantity.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "protectionism" and state two methods other than tariffs.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Protectionism is the use of government policies to shield domestic industries from foreign competition. (1) Quotas — quantitative limits on the volume of imports allowed. (1) Subsidies to domestic firms — reducing their costs to make them more competitive against imports without raising consumer prices directly.' },
      { q: 'Explain why exchange rate volatility may discourage international trade.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Exchange rate fluctuations create uncertainty about the domestic currency value of future export revenues and import costs. (1) This uncertainty makes it difficult for firms to plan, set prices, and calculate profit margins on international contracts. (1) Risk-averse firms may choose not to trade internationally or must pay for expensive hedging (forward contracts), raising transaction costs and reducing trade volumes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "export-led growth" and why some East Asian economies pursued it.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Export-led growth is a development strategy focused on producing goods for international markets rather than just domestic consumption. (1) It allows countries to exploit comparative advantage and benefit from economies of scale in larger global markets. (1) Export earnings provide foreign exchange to import capital goods needed for further development. (1) East Asian economies (South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore) used this strategy with government support (industrial policy, undervalued currencies) to achieve rapid industrialisation and sustained growth.' },
      { q: 'State two roles of the World Trade Organisation (WTO).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) To provide a framework of rules for international trade and negotiate multilateral reductions in trade barriers. (1) To settle trade disputes between member nations through its dispute resolution mechanism, preventing trade wars.' },
      { q: 'Explain how improvements in the terms of trade can have both positive and negative effects on an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Positive: each unit of exports now buys more imports — the country can afford more imported goods for the same volume of exports (improved purchasing power). (1) Living standards may rise as imported consumer goods become relatively cheaper. (1) Negative: more expensive exports may reduce competitiveness and demand for exports if demand is elastic. (1) Export industries may contract, causing unemployment and a worsening trade balance if export volumes fall significantly.' },
      { q: 'Define "foreign exchange reserves" and explain one reason why a country holds them.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Foreign exchange reserves are holdings of foreign currencies, gold, and other internationally accepted assets held by the central bank. (1) They are held to intervene in foreign exchange markets to stabilise or maintain the exchange rate. (1) They also provide confidence to international investors and act as a buffer to finance imports or repay foreign debt during economic shocks.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a country might choose to impose anti-dumping duties.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Anti-dumping duties are tariffs imposed specifically to counteract goods being sold below cost or below home-market price. (1) They protect domestic industries from unfair competition that could destroy efficient firms unable to match artificially low prices. (1) Without protection, domestic firms may exit the market, after which the dumping firm raises prices as a monopolist — so anti-dumping duties prevent long-run consumer harm.' },
      { q: 'Explain why developing countries may face deteriorating terms of trade over time.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Many developing countries export primary commodities with low income elasticity of demand — as world incomes grow, demand for their exports grows slowly. (1) Meanwhile, they import manufactured goods and services with high income elasticity — import spending rises faster than export revenue. (1) Over-supply of commodities by many developing countries drives down prices, while manufactured import prices tend to rise — the Prebisch-Singer hypothesis.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how the demand for and supply of a currency determine the exchange rate in a floating system.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) Axes correctly labelled: exchange rate (price of currency) on vertical, quantity of currency on horizontal. (1) Downward-sloping demand curve for the currency (demand from foreigners wanting to buy UK exports/invest). (1) Upward-sloping supply curve (supply from domestic agents wanting to buy imports/invest abroad). (1) Equilibrium exchange rate determined where supply equals demand, with clear labelling.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "strategic trade theory" and how it differs from classical free trade theory.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Strategic trade theory argues that government intervention (subsidies, protection) can help domestic firms gain competitive advantage in industries with significant economies of scale and first-mover advantages. (1) In industries with high barriers to entry, early support can help domestic firms achieve scale before foreign rivals, capturing supernormal profits. (1) This contrasts with classical theory which argues all intervention reduces welfare below the free trade optimum. (1) However, it risks retaliation from trading partners and assumes governments can accurately identify winning industries (picking winners problem).' },
      { q: 'Explain why bilateral trade deals may be preferable to multilateral negotiations for some countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Bilateral deals are faster to negotiate — only two parties need to agree rather than 160+ WTO members. (1) They can be tailored to the specific needs and strengths of both countries (e.g., focusing on sectors of mutual interest). (1) Larger economies can use their bargaining power to secure favourable terms that would be impossible in multilateral forums where smaller nations have equal voice.' },
      { q: 'State two components of the financial account of the balance of payments.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Foreign direct investment (FDI) — long-term investment by firms in productive assets abroad (e.g., building factories). (1) Portfolio investment — purchases of foreign financial assets (shares, bonds) without controlling interest in the company.' }
    ]
  },
  '4.2': {
    name: 'Poverty, Inequality & Development',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define "absolute poverty".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A condition where individuals\' income is insufficient (1) to afford the minimum necessities for physical survival (food, clean water, shelter, basic healthcare).' },
      { q: 'State two differences between economic growth and economic development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Growth is a quantitative increase in real GDP/national output, while development is a qualitative improvement in living standards and wellbeing. (1) Growth can occur without development (e.g., if benefits accrue only to elites), but development encompasses reduced poverty, better health, education, and freedom.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Gini coefficient is used to measure inequality.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The Gini coefficient is derived from the Lorenz curve — it measures the area between the Lorenz curve and the line of perfect equality. (1) It ranges from 0 (perfect equality — everyone has equal income) to 1 (perfect inequality — one person has all income). (1) A higher Gini coefficient indicates greater income inequality within a country.' },
      { q: 'State two components of the Human Development Index (HDI).', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Life expectancy at birth — measuring health and longevity. (1) Mean years and expected years of schooling — measuring education and knowledge.' },
      { q: 'Explain the poverty trap (cycle of poverty) in a developing country.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Low incomes mean low savings and consumption focused on basic survival. (1) Low savings means low investment in physical and human capital. (1) Low investment leads to low productivity growth and limited job creation. (1) This perpetuates low incomes — the cycle repeats across generations unless broken by external intervention (aid, education, investment).' },
      { q: 'Explain two ways in which corruption hinders economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Corruption diverts public funds from productive uses (schools, hospitals, infrastructure) into private pockets, reducing the effectiveness of government spending. (1) It deters foreign direct investment as firms face unpredictable bribery costs and an unreliable legal environment. (1) It distorts resource allocation — contracts go to those with political connections rather than the most efficient providers. (1) It undermines trust in institutions, discouraging entrepreneurship and domestic investment.' },
      { q: 'Define "foreign aid".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Financial or technical assistance provided by governments, international organisations, or NGOs (1) to developing countries to promote economic development and welfare, usually on concessional terms (below market rate or as grants).' },
      { q: 'Explain the Harrod-Domar model and its implications for development policy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The model states: Growth rate = Savings ratio / Capital-output ratio. (1) Growth requires investment, which requires savings to fund it. (1) For developing countries with low domestic savings, the model implies a need to fill the savings gap through foreign aid, FDI, or borrowing. (1) Policy implication: policies should focus on increasing the savings rate and improving the efficiency of capital use (lowering the capital-output ratio).' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of using GDP per capita to compare levels of development between countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) It does not reflect income distribution — a country with high GDP per capita may have extreme inequality with widespread poverty. (1) It ignores non-income dimensions of development: health, education, freedom, environmental quality, and personal security.' },
      { q: 'Explain how microfinance can promote development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Microfinance provides small loans to people excluded from traditional banking (no collateral, low income). (1) This enables individuals to start or expand small businesses, generating income and employment. (1) It particularly empowers women, who are the majority of borrowers, improving gender equality and household welfare.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "resource curse" (paradox of plenty).', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Countries with abundant natural resources (oil, minerals) may experience slower economic growth and worse development outcomes than resource-poor countries. (1) Resource wealth can fuel corruption and rent-seeking as elites compete to control resource revenues. (1) "Dutch disease" occurs when resource exports appreciate the exchange rate, making other exports uncompetitive and deindustrialising the economy. (1) Volatile commodity prices create fiscal instability, and dependency on resource exports discourages economic diversification.' },
      { q: 'State two market-oriented strategies for promoting development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Trade liberalisation — reducing tariffs and quotas to integrate with global markets and attract export-oriented FDI. (1) Privatisation — transferring state-owned enterprises to private ownership to improve efficiency through the profit motive and competition.' },
      { q: 'Explain why investment in female education is considered particularly effective for development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Educated women tend to have fewer children, reducing population pressure on resources and services. (1) They earn higher incomes, improving household living standards and nutrition. (1) They invest more in their children\'s health and education, creating positive intergenerational effects. (1) Greater female workforce participation increases total economic output and GDP growth.' },
      { q: 'Define "sustainable development".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Development that meets the needs of the present generation (1) without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs, balancing economic, social, and environmental objectives.' },
      { q: 'Explain two limitations of foreign aid as a strategy for development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Aid dependency — countries may become reliant on aid flows rather than developing domestic revenue sources, creating vulnerability to donor decisions. (1) Corruption may divert aid from its intended purpose, with funds captured by elites rather than reaching the poor. (1) Tied aid (requiring purchase of donor-country goods/services) may not align with recipient priorities. (1) Aid may distort local markets — e.g., food aid depressing prices for local farmers.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the Lorenz curve and the Gini coefficient as measures of inequality.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) The Lorenz curve is a graphical representation showing the cumulative share of income earned by the cumulative percentage of the population. (1) The Gini coefficient is a single numerical value derived from the Lorenz curve (area between line of equality and Lorenz curve, divided by total area under line of equality). (1) The Lorenz curve shows the pattern of distribution visually, while the Gini gives a summary statistic for easy comparison between countries or over time.' },
      { q: 'State two barriers to development that are geographical/physical in nature.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Being landlocked — no access to sea ports raises transport costs for trade. (1) Tropical climate — increasing disease burden (malaria, dengue) which reduces labour productivity and diverts health spending.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Lewis dual-sector model describes the process of economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The economy has two sectors: a traditional agricultural sector with surplus (underemployed) labour and a modern industrial/urban sector. (1) Development occurs as surplus labour transfers from agriculture to industry. (1) In the modern sector, workers are more productive and paid a wage above subsistence, generating profits for capitalists. (1) These profits are reinvested in more capital and expansion, drawing further labour from agriculture until the surplus is exhausted — at which point wages begin to rise economy-wide.' },
      { q: 'State two ways in which globalisation may have negative effects on developing countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) MNCs may exploit weak labour and environmental regulations, extracting value without sustainable local benefit. (1) Trade liberalisation can destroy infant industries before they become competitive, increasing dependency on primary commodity exports with volatile prices.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the Washington Consensus policies have been criticised as a development strategy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Rapid trade liberalisation exposed fragile domestic industries to overwhelming foreign competition, causing deindustrialisation. (1) Privatisation sometimes transferred state assets to elites at below-market prices without improving service delivery. (1) Fiscal austerity reduced spending on essential services (health, education) that underpin long-term development. (1) The one-size-fits-all approach ignored different countries\' institutional contexts, stages of development, and specific challenges.' },
      { q: 'Define "relative poverty".', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) A condition where an individual\'s income falls below a certain proportion of the average or median income in their society (1) — they cannot afford the standard of living considered normal in that country (e.g., below 60% of median income in the UK).' },
      { q: 'Explain why rapid population growth can hinder economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) If population grows faster than GDP, GDP per capita falls even if total output is rising. (1) Rapid growth increases dependency ratios — fewer working-age adults support more children, reducing savings and investment. (1) Pressure on public services (schools, hospitals) means resources are spread thinly, reducing quality. (1) Environmental pressure from population growth can degrade natural capital (deforestation, water scarcity), undermining long-term sustainability.' },
      { q: 'Explain how property rights and the rule of law support economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Secure property rights give individuals and firms confidence to invest, knowing their assets cannot be arbitrarily confiscated. (1) They allow land and property to be used as collateral for borrowing, unlocking capital for entrepreneurship. (1) The rule of law ensures contracts are enforced, reducing transaction costs and enabling complex economic relationships. (1) Together they attract FDI, as foreign firms need confidence that investments will be protected and profits can be repatriated.' },
      { q: 'State two non-income measures of development besides HDI.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) The Multidimensional Poverty Index (MPI) — measures deprivation across health, education, and living standards simultaneously. (1) The Gender Inequality Index (GII) — measures gender-based disadvantage in reproductive health, empowerment, and labour market participation.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "Dutch disease" and how it hinders diversification.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Dutch disease occurs when a booming natural resource sector causes the exchange rate to appreciate. (1) The strong currency makes non-resource exports (manufacturing, agriculture) uncompetitive on world markets. (1) These sectors contract (deindustrialisation) as they cannot compete at the appreciated exchange rate. (1) The economy becomes increasingly dependent on the resource sector, making it vulnerable to commodity price crashes and reducing structural diversity needed for sustainable development.' },
      { q: 'Explain why debt relief may be more effective than new aid for heavily indebted poor countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Heavily indebted countries spend large proportions of export earnings on debt service (interest and repayments), diverting funds from development spending. (1) Debt relief frees up government revenue to be spent on health, education, and infrastructure directly. (1) It removes the debt overhang that deters private investment — firms are reluctant to invest in countries where future tax revenue may be claimed by creditors. (1) Unlike new aid which may create further dependency, debt relief provides a clean slate and greater fiscal autonomy for domestic policy choices.' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of institutions in economic development, using one example.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Institutions are the formal and informal rules that govern economic behaviour — legal systems, regulatory bodies, governance structures, and social norms. (1) Good institutions reduce uncertainty and transaction costs, encouraging investment and exchange. (1) Example: an independent judiciary that enforces contracts fairly gives businesses confidence to trade and invest long-term. (1) Weak institutions (corruption, arbitrary rule, weak property rights) deter investment and lead to rent-seeking rather than productive activity.' },
      { q: 'State the difference between bilateral aid and multilateral aid.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Bilateral aid flows directly from one donor government to one recipient country — the donor retains control over allocation and conditions. (1) Multilateral aid is channelled through international organisations (World Bank, UN agencies) which pool funds from multiple donors and allocate according to their own criteria.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, draw a Lorenz curve showing high inequality and identify the Gini coefficient area.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '(1) 45-degree line of perfect equality drawn from origin to (100,100). (1) Lorenz curve drawn significantly bowed away from the line of equality (indicating high inequality). (1) Gini coefficient area correctly identified as the area between the line of equality and the Lorenz curve, divided by the total area under the line of equality.' },
      { q: 'Explain how import substitution industrialisation (ISI) works as a development strategy and state one criticism.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) ISI involves protecting domestic industries from foreign competition through tariffs and quotas, allowing them to develop without facing established foreign firms. (1) The aim is to replace imported manufactured goods with domestically produced ones, reducing dependency on foreign goods. (1) Protected industries should eventually become competitive enough to export. (1) Criticism: protected firms may never become efficient due to lack of competition — they remain permanently dependent on protection and consumers pay higher prices for lower-quality goods.' },
      { q: 'Explain why remittances from migrant workers can promote development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Remittances provide a direct flow of foreign exchange to households in developing countries, often exceeding foreign aid in total value. (1) They increase household income, allowing spending on education, healthcare, and small business investment. (1) Unlike aid, remittances go directly to families (bypassing potentially corrupt governments) and are a stable income source even during domestic economic downturns.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between income inequality and wealth inequality.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Income inequality refers to the unequal distribution of earnings and transfers received over a period (wages, profits, benefits). (1) Wealth inequality refers to the unequal distribution of accumulated assets (property, savings, shares, pensions) — the stock of value owned. (1) Wealth inequality is typically much greater than income inequality because wealth accumulates over generations and earns returns (interest, dividends, capital gains) that further concentrate it.' },
      { q: 'Explain how conditional cash transfers (CCTs) can help reduce poverty while promoting human capital development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) CCTs provide regular payments to poor households on condition that they meet certain requirements (e.g., children attend school, family attends health checkups). (1) The cash transfer directly reduces absolute poverty by increasing household income for basic needs. (1) The conditions incentivise investment in human capital — education and healthcare attendance — that breaks the intergenerational poverty cycle. (1) Evidence from programmes like Brazil\'s Bolsa Familia shows improved school enrollment, vaccination rates, and nutrition alongside poverty reduction.' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why economic growth alone may not reduce inequality in a developing country.', marks: 2, markScheme: '(1) Growth may be concentrated in capital-intensive sectors or urban areas, benefiting owners of capital and the already-employed rather than the rural poor. (1) Without progressive taxation and redistribution policies, the gains from growth accrue disproportionately to the wealthy, potentially widening the gap.' },
      { q: 'Explain the Todaro model of rural-urban migration and why it may lead to urban unemployment.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) The Todaro model argues that rural workers migrate to cities based on expected income — the urban wage multiplied by the probability of finding a job. (1) Even if urban unemployment is high, the expected income may exceed certain rural earnings if the urban wage is much higher. (1) Rational workers therefore continue migrating as long as expected urban income exceeds rural income. (1) This leads to excessive migration, swelling urban populations beyond available jobs, creating slums, informal employment, and persistent urban unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why access to financial services (financial inclusion) is important for development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Access to savings accounts allows poor households to accumulate funds for investment, education, or emergencies without risk of theft. (1) Access to credit enables small businesses to invest and grow, creating employment and income. (1) Insurance products help households manage risks (crop failure, illness) without falling back into poverty — reducing vulnerability and encouraging productive risk-taking.' },
      { q: 'Explain two reasons why fair trade schemes may have limited impact on development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) Fair trade covers only a small percentage of total trade in commodities — most producers are not certified and do not benefit. (1) The price premium may be captured by intermediaries or certification bodies rather than reaching individual farmers. (1) Guaranteed higher prices may discourage diversification into higher-value activities, keeping farmers dependent on primary commodities. (1) The additional costs of certification (standards, audits) may exclude the poorest producers who most need support.' },
      { q: 'Define "human capital" and explain its importance for economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(1) Human capital refers to the stock of knowledge, skills, health, and capabilities embodied in the labour force that makes workers productive. (1) Investment in human capital (education, training, healthcare) increases labour productivity, enabling higher output per worker and sustained economic growth. (1) Countries with higher human capital attract more FDI, develop more innovative industries, and can transition from low-skill primary production to higher-value manufacturing and services.' },
      { q: 'Explain why inequality may actually hinder economic growth in developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '(1) High inequality means the poor cannot invest in their own human capital (education, health) — talent is wasted, reducing aggregate productivity. (1) The poor have limited access to credit markets, preventing them from starting businesses or investing in productive assets. (1) Political instability and social unrest associated with extreme inequality deter domestic and foreign investment. (1) Highly unequal societies may create extractive institutions where elites block reforms that would promote broad-based growth.' }
    ]
  }
};

